<subSubSection pageId="21" pageNumber="422" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="21.[151,1437,151,501]" pageId="21" pageNumber="422">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,352,332,357]" pageId="21" pageNumber="422">Distribution.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ayala" authorityYear="2017" box="[360,526,332,356]" class="Insecta" family="Colletidae" genus="Colletes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="422" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="solari">
<emphasis box="[360,526,332,356]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="422">Colletes solari</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distributed in the pine forest remnants of Talpa, 
<collectingRegion box="[1108,1187,332,357]" country="Mexico" name="Jalisco" pageId="21" pageNumber="422">Jalisco</collectingRegion>
, towards the pine-oak forests of Altos de 
<collectingRegion box="[383,473,367,392]" country="Mexico" name="Chiapas" pageId="21" pageNumber="422">Chiapas</collectingRegion>
province. This species probably has a wider distribution, following those vegetal communities of Transmexican Volcanic Belt (
<figureCitation box="[664,748,404,429]" captionStart="FIGURES 57 – 58. 57" captionStartId="20.[151,264,1876,1899]" captionTargetBox="[514,1092,1007,1817]" captionTargetId="figure@20.[470,1116,949,1856]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURES 57 – 58. 57 — Map of collecting localities for Colletes jobeli, C. isabelae, C. jaliscoensis and C. nigerrima. 58 — Map of collecting localities for C. solari, C. tzotzilis, C. chiaPensis, and C. guatemalensis." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1051949/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="422">Fig. 58</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="21" pageNumber="422" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="21.[151,1437,151,501]" pageId="21" pageNumber="422">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,439,464]" pageId="21" pageNumber="422">Remarks.</emphasis>
In some male specimens, the wing tonality may be amber and the legs have a brownish integument. Likewise, the central stria of the basal area of the propodeum may be simple.
